data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, new built-in `Span<T>` conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so it throws at runtime.

## How to fix it

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these will pin the call to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable in an expression tree.
